name: SMART - Red Sector A
description:
Endurance workout with low rest time, taken and adapted from a training book by Guy Thibault, a Quebec exercise scientist who does research on cycling training and physiology. The book was (and still is) my main training reference from before Xert and power meters era. 

The no-power instructions are to start at a sustainable pace and increase intensity as the intervals get shorter. I've set up the power in reference to TP, which can be changed to adjust the difficulty level (±5% TP to all sets of intervals). If you still have some juice left at the end, you can push harder than prescribe on the last set of intervals (1-min).

When directing that workout in a spinning class (by feeling, without power), I set up the playlist to have Red Sector A, by Rush, starting around the 2-minutes intervals, when things start getting... red.

"All that we can do is just survive
All that we can do to help ourselves is stay alive"

name: Cheung CX - Draining the Swamp
description: CX is all about starting out hard, being able to sustain that hard effort, and then repeatedly surge even while under fatigue. Each interval set is about 6 minutes, simulating about 2/3 - 3/4 of a lap effort. You can vary the intervals by alternating higher gear and lower gear efforts to teach your legs the necessary snap to accelerate out of corners. The difficulty of this workout also comes from just enough recovery to get back to full MPA before starting the next interval.

name: Cheung CX - Hot Laps
description: These simulate the extremely hard first lap of a CX race, with a massive sprint off the line, then repeated surges for positioning through the first 3/4 of a lap or thereabouts. In between are single hard sprints off the line.

name: Cheung CX - 2x25 min Over-Unders
description: CX is all about variability in power output. So even when you are working on building your aerobic capacity it is important to keep that stochastic stimulus on your neuromuscular system. Another way to approach these intervals is to keep the cadence high during the easier efforts, then shift to a harder gear just before each burst, forcing yourself to apply even more torque. This workout can be done several times a week as a foundation for maintaining aerobic capacity throughout the CX season.

name: Cheung CX - Ronnestad
description: This is a really challenging workout (see the extremely high Difficulty Score) that is almost guaranteed to gain you a medal and reset your Fitness Signature. This is especially true for Fitness Signatures with a relatively high TP and low HIE/PP components. This workout is taken from a Ronnestad et al. study on front-load periodization that used this workout to greatly increase VO2max. The short 15 s of recovery between each interval are extremely short, but they will get you ready for the repeated surges out of every corner.

name: Cheung CX - 3x20 min Over-Unders
description: For those where 2x20 is not enough. CX is all about variability in power output. So even when you are working on building your aerobic capacity it is important to keep that stochastic stimulus on your neuromuscular system. Another way to approach these intervals is to keep the cadence high during the easier efforts, then shift to a harder gear just before each burst, forcing yourself to apply even more torque. This workout can be done several times a week as a foundation for maintaining aerobic capacity throughout the CX season.

name: Cheung - Come As You Are
description: Working mostly at or near your LTP for steady endurance efforts. With endurance work and especially on the trainer, one good habit is to shake up your cadence. Try doing each of the steps in different gears and cadences, ranging from 70-100+ rpm. Really helps to maintain snap and work different muscles.

name: Cheung - People Get Ready
description: Especially on a trainer, it is great practice to switch up cadences to activate a range of muscles. During the 4x5 min efforts at 110% LTP, do them at 70/80/90/100 rpm.

name: Cheung CX - Stomping Tom
description: This workout targets the ability to quickly lay out bursts of power, maintain a high intensity right around threshold, then lay out bursts of power again after sustained fatigue. Aim to do these in one gear higher than typical and also seated to replicate the way you would apply power on the CX course

name: SMART - No Time To Cry - 69 min
description: Threshold training doesn't have to be about 20 minute intervals.  Keep things interesting with this varying sweet-spot workout, extended for greater XSS.

name: Cheung - Don't Look Back in Anger
description: Predominantly LTP workout, with enough variety to keep things interesting.

name: SMART - Homemade Dynamite
description: Dynamite, fireworks, it's all the same to us. If you want to build the ability to 'light it up', this is a great workout. Build up some difficulty, then punch it. As a short workout, ANYONE can fit this in.

name: Where The Streets Have No Name
description: Need to cram in a quick, but effective, workout? This is a great workout before you get into over/unders. Because it's a step lower than typical over/unders, it's also a great indoor workout when you find you can't hit the same power inside as outside.

name: CX 15/15's
description: This is a difficult - but not impossible workout - workout to develop the variability needed to accelerate repeatedly, like in a CX race.

name: SMART CX Twenty-Tens
description: This workout is pretty tough and it will make you even tougher. Tough enough for the demands of cyclocross. If you're getting a lot of rest you can do this up to twice per week, but if you're not - best to do this once per week at most. Take it very easy between intervals so that you're fully recovered before you start the next set.

name: SMART - Two Step
description: Need to cram in a quick, but effective, workout? Doing the 'high' steps of this workout in a bigger gear & lower cadence than you're used to - say 65 RPM - is a great way to build strength around your hips. Over the course of 45 minutes, you'll spend over 30 minutes at a Strain rate of 75-100 XSS/hr (XSSR).

name: Eight Days A Week
description: Need to cram in a quick, but effective, workout? Accumulate a dozen minutes at your 10 minute MMP to build your climber focus.

name: CX 2by2's
description: This is a great workout early in your prep for the CX or other race season because it begins to push you into the red. With relatively short recoveries between efforts, you'll stimulate your system to adapt to changes in pace and more taxing efforts. These are great indoors on the trainer or outdoors on the open road...

name: SMART CX 15/15's
description: This is a SMART version of the basic 15/15 workout to develop the variability needed to accelerate repeatedly, like in a CX race.  Because it's a SMART workout, intervals won't always be 15s - that will depend on how you execute them. If you're doing these on a smart/power-enabled trainer, choose a big gear (high wheel speed) to do the intervals with lower torque.

name: CX Twenty-Tens
description: This workout is very tough and it will make you even tougher. Tough enough for the demands of cyclocross. If you're getting a lot of rest you can do this up to twice per week, but if you're not - best to do this once per week at most. Take it very easy between intervals so that you're fully recovered before you start the next set.

name: SMART Xert Zwift Surplus Seeker 75min
description: This workout is similar to the weekly Zwift group ride called "Xert Surplus Seeker Ride". Most of the riding is around your LTP with a few short surges to get over the top of the climb, or to catch back on the group, every lap.

name: SMART - Hold Me, Thrill Me, Kiss Me, Kill Me
description: Need to cram in a quick, but effective, workout? Four supra-threshold efforts with just enough time between them to (almost) recover completely will get the job done.

name: Take Me To Church
description: This is a pure endurance workout to build your Lower Threshold Power. Unless you like riding indoors more than outdoors, most riders will elect to simulate this workout outdoors. A few hills and a long time in the saddle give it a 2.5 Moderate difficulty rating to build your 'go all day' power. "To keep the goddess on my side, she demands a sacrifice..."

name: Flume +2 (Copy)
description:
VO2max workouts in general target your aerobic power, pain tolerance, muscular recruitment - both in terms of how hard and how quickly you can muster that strength - and muscle endurance in a manner that coaxes you into doing a whole lot of repeats.

Race simulation workouts like this one allow you to accumulate a hefty amount of time at VO2max power, all inside a reasonably short workout (even if you skip a repeat here and there).

So work toward that middle set - the peak of the pyramid - and then fight hard to last through the end of the workout knowing that each additional set, each additional repeat, can make you stronger, tougher and more capable on the race course.

Important: Performing these intervals at 125% FTP assumes you can complete the intervals with few/no breaks. If you're frequently skipping repeats or backpedaling during the brief floats, reduce the Workout Intensity to your repeatable aerobic power.

name: Williamson +4
description:
Goals
Improvements in Anaerobic Capacity largely target increased times to exhaustion at levels well above FTP & even VO2max and decreasing recovery forces the aerobic system to take up the slack left by an under-recovered anaerobic system.

The benefits of training at intensities this high are plentiful and wide-ranging. From improved lactate processing capabilities & acidic tolerance to greater levels of muscle fiber recruitment & increased fiber size, i.e. work capacity, AC training is painful but productive. These efforts are especially useful for mountain bikers, cyclocross racers, road racers & criterium riders.

Shoot for high-rpm spins (100-120rpm), the higher the watts, the faster the spin.

name: Mallory +1
description:
mimic the demands of working in a tightly organized, hard-charging paceline where each rider not only takes a hard, 15-second pull every minute but increases the overall power output every couple of minutes.

The goals are steady cadence regardless of effort, lactate tolerance, and muscular endurance.

The relatively short but highly demanding VO2max efforts target aerobic power and high-intensity repeatability.

Put the two interval types together and you have the makings for a rigorous race simulation reserved for riders at the top of their form.

Keep your spin steady during the over-unders, 85rpm or higher, and try for a high but steady cadence during the VO2max jobbers, 100+rpm.

You can also work in and out of the saddle during the OU's or even go aero/non-aero to dress things up a bit and tailor the intervals to your needs.
